Build a Personal Portfolio with a Static Website Generator (Jinja2)

  • Report this article
Manoj Kumar

Manoj Kumar

Published Jun 29, 2025
+ Follow

Maintaining a multi-page static website manually? It can get messyespecially when every page shares a common navigation bar, footer, and header elements like Google Analytics. Every small update turns into a full-blown copy-paste exercise.

Lets fix that.

In this post, youll learn how to use a static website generator powered by Jinja2 templates to create a clean, reusable structure for your personal portfolio, GitHub project pages, and more.

Why Use a Static Website Generator?

If you're building with plain HTML, updating content across multiple pagessuch as social media links, page titles, or tracking codeis inefficient. A Jinja2 static site generator lets you:

  • Centralize reusable components (like headers, footers)
  • Automate HTML templating
  • Improve scalability and maintainability
  • Keep your static site SEO-friendly

Use Case: Portfolio with Jinja2

Lets say your static site includes: similar to this sample static website

  • A Home, About, and Contact page
  • A shared footer with social media links
  • A common navbar for navigation
  • Embedded Google Analytics in the <head>
  • Unique meta titles for each page

Heres how to do it:

Step-by-Step Setup

Step 1: Clone the GitHub Repository

To add Google Analytics

Open: templates/_base.html Paste your tracking code inside the <head> section. This keeps analytics consistent across your static pages.

To customize Footer with Social Media Links

Open: templates/partials/_footer.html Replace placeholder icons and URLs with your actual social media profile links.

Set Page Titles with Jinja2 Blocks

Want SEO-optimized page titles? On each page add the title in the : 

{% block title %}About | github-pages-templates{% endblock %}

To add / update Page Content

Within each file, add your content under:

{% block body %}

<div class="row">

<div class="col-12 text-left">

<!-- Your custom HTML here -->

</div>

</div>

{% endblock %}

Generate the Static Website

Once you've made your changes, follow the steps in the README to build and deploy your site. Now your static website is clean, consistent, and easy to updatewithout repetitive edits.
